{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"A\n    \n      Native Migration + React Native Compat UI\n      Recommended\n      \n        Migration layer: Swift code in ios/Shared/ reads Core Data + old UserDefaults on first launch, converts to v2 profiles, writes via KeyboardPreferences. Runs before React Native loads.\n        Compat UI: New React Native screen (ClassicEditorScreen) with the flat v1-style settings list. Reads/writes v2 profile model. Available via toggle in the main editor.\n        Detection: Swift checks for Core Data store existence + migration flag in UserDefaults.\n      \n      \n        Pros\n          Migration happens at native layer - fast, reliable, before RN loads\n          Core Data reading is natural in Swift\n          Compat UI reuses existing RN components\n          Clean separation: native handles data, RN handles UI\n        \n        Cons\n          Migration logic in Swift only (not Android) - but v1 was iOS-only anyway\n          Two separate codebases for migration (Swift) and compat UI (RN)","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1773680732735}
